"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[4824],{2443:e=>{e.exports=JSON.parse('{"id":1,"title":"Chapter\xa01\xa0: Problem, Consciousness, Solution","description":"","content":{"html":"<h2 id=\\"f02b72a5-ee6a-45b2-a44f-25d6417e1c72\\">Introduction</h2>\\n<p>The purpose of this chapter is to present the following vision and explain it in detail: the modern world seems too complex for the human mind. But human intelligence has been progressing since the dawn of humanity, thanks to science and technology. Consequently, computer science, the internet, and AI will enable us to overcome the complexity of modern challenges. And this will not happen naturally, but precisely through the use of our consciousness and our will.</p>\\n<p>I will begin this chapter by addressing what is likely your biggest objection: <em>how can we speak of progress in intelligence today, when the intellectual level of the population seems to be collapsing with social media, TikTok, etc.?</em></p>\\n<h2 id=\\"2dba957d-d122-4740-8303-6ccaf607089b\\">Why is the Current Intellectual Collapse an Optical Illusion?</h2>\\n<img src=\\"/media/futur_intelligence_maj_elite_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n<p>Indeed, the generation that has just spent its youth watching mindless videos on TikTok, Instagram, or YouTube will likely be the dumbest and most antisocial generation in History. But at the same time, some will have spent their youth watching lectures from the world\'s top universities at x2 speed, with an almost omniscient tutor named ChatGPT. All of this from a smartphone in the palm of their hand, during their commutes, meals, workouts, and, most importantly, for free. In other words, on average, the next generation will likely be dumber than before, but its \\"elites\\" will be the brightest History has ever known.</p>\\n<p>No pessimism here, just an observation. It would be entirely possible to completely reform the education system so that the average level skyrocket while reducing inequality and the cost of education. And that, in fact, is one of the tasks of the Metarevolution we\'ll discuss in <a href=\\"/missions/1\\">this article</a>.</p>\\n<p>To return to the original issue, indeed, the average of humanity may not be heading toward <em>ever greater intelligence</em>, but its \\"elites\\" certainly are. And it is these \\"elites\\" who drive science, technology, and social organizations forward and, more broadly, who build and run the world.</p>\\n<p>On peut r\xe9sumer cette id\xe9e par : <em>il n\'a jamais \xe9t\xe9 aussi facile de s\'\xe9lever, comme de ne rien faire</em>. Le niveau minimal d\'intelligence et d\'\xe9ducation pour vivre \\"normalement\\" en soci\xe9t\xe9 a beaucoup diminu\xe9. Mais, en m\xeame temps, le niveau maximal d\'intelligence et d\'\xe9ducation humainement atteignable a fortement augment\xe9. Autrement dit, l\'intelligence humaine a litt\xe9ralement progress\xe9.</p>\\n<p>Note that I use the term \\"elite\\" regardless of social background, because we will have the most brilliant sons of working-class families in History, and at the same time, the heirs from the wealthiest families, the dumbest and most antisocial in that same History. Furthermore, the \\"elites\\" I am referring to will excel in all professional fields. We will therefore have the most brilliant physicists, but also architects, athletes, mayors, plumbers, and farmers in History.</p>\\n<p>This dynamic can be illustrated with an image:</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/evolution_mini_max_intelligence_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 700px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>the concept of the <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Welfare_state\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">\\"welfare state\\"</a> is illustrated by the implementation of social spending (unemployment benefits, health insurance, pensions, support for families, people with disabilities, or the needy, etc.).</em></p>\\n<p>This idea can be summarized as: <em>it has never been easier to rise up, or to do nothing</em>. The minimum level of intelligence and education required to live \\"normally\\" in society has decreased significantly. But at the same time, the maximum level of intelligence and education that humans can achieve has increased dramatically. In other words, human intelligence has literally advanced.</p>\\n<p>What exactly does that mean? Has the human brain evolved over the past few centuries? No, the \\"raw power\\" of the human brain has remained the same. However, its actual performance has indeed increased. It\'s exactly the same as when you shift into a higher gear in a car—you can go faster with the same engine. You may have a 190-horsepower engine, but if you stay stuck in first gear, you won\'t go faster than 60 km/h.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/rapport_vitesse.jpeg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>the power delivered by the engine varies depending on the \\"engine speed\\" (the number of revolutions per minute), which is not shown in the image, and an engine is characterized by its maximum power—in this case, 190 hp on an Audi A4 40 TFSI (source: <a href=\\"https://www.guillaumedarding.fr/technique-de-conduite-acceleration-et-reprise-3174106.html\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">guillaumedarding.fr</a>).</em></p>\\n<p>That being said, we might ask ourselves: if the internet and computing are increasing human intelligence, could this increase in intelligence enable humanity to cope with the complexity of the modern world? In short, to find real solutions to current social, economic, ecological, and other problems?</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"ad4b9403-c99c-4dbb-90cd-2a7098edcaec\\">At the Dawn of an Intellectual Revolution</h2>\\n<p>In the introduction to this manifesto, I mentioned that politicians and intellectuals have simply given up in the face of the modern world\'s complexity over the past 30 years. But there may be a reason for this: the modern world may have truly been too complex for the human mind before the internet and computers.</p>\\n<p>I\'ve been harsh on intellectuals because I hold them responsible for the problems we face in the West. But now, it\'s a matter of being fair. Indeed, it\'s fairly easy for me—and even more so for the younger generations who\'ve always known the internet—to criticize the intellectual limitations of previous generations. But let\'s take a step back.</p>\\n<p>Just 10 years ago, the content available for free on the internet was extremely limited compared to today. The quality of online content has skyrocketed, particularly during the pandemic, as lockdowns led many skilled individuals to create content. That is to say:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>As part of their work (forced digital transition)</li>\\n<li>To keep themselves occupied and cope with boredom during long months of confinement at home</li>\\n<li>By discovering the entrepreneurial opportunities offered by the internet (encouraged by the acceleration of the digital transition)</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>If we go back further, 20 years ago, the internet wasn\'t yet available in all rural areas, or its speed was so slow that it didn\'t really allow for internet use. Concretely, you had to let YouTube videos load at 240p resolution. Watching at 1x speed was therefore impossible, and 2x speed was out of the question. In other words, in 20 years, the speed of communication and learning has potentially doubled—literally.</p>\\n<p>We could also, of course, mention recent advancements in AI that have increased the speed of information retrieval tenfold. For example, it is now technically possible to read excellent summaries of 10 books a day by feeding the PDFs to <a href=\\"https://notebooklm.google/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">NotebookLM</a>. This would have taken at least 10 times longer before, by skimming through the books.</p>\\n<p>If we go back even further, access to information in the \\"pre-internet\\" world was very different. Today, we have access to the best lectures and conferences in history for free and without restriction right on our cell phones. Back then, you first had to hear about a lecture, a conference, or a book and actually be able to get to it. So, for starters, if you didn\'t live in a big city, you literally had access to <em>no</em> conferences without driving two hours (imagine having access not to one or two average YouTube videos a day, but to <em>none</em>). And even in the city, access to courses and lectures was limited, at least by the size of the lecture halls and the requirements for admission (such as being a student at the school in question).</p>\\n<p><strong>To understand the magnitude of this change, I need to tell you about my own experience and how I came up with this manifesto.</strong></p>\\n<p>For the past 10 years, I\'ve spent about 1 in every 4 daily activities (exercise, cooking, eating, walking, commuting, etc.) listening to lectures on YouTube or audiobooks. To give you a concrete example, I listened to the <a href=\\"https://youtube.com/playlist?list=PLOj9pZ2YNGZ_OU2P9oJmTSfviaHf3HYey&#x26;si=5DcdtGBHHLyoIW38\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">courses on experimental cognitive psychology</a> by Stanislas Dehaene at the <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coll%C3%A8ge_de_France\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Coll\xe8ge de France</a> while doing push-ups and pull-ups. And I listened to an insane number of lectures by historians while I was running (this lifestyle is nothing out of the ordinary today and is by no means \\"futuristic\\"<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-1\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-1\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">1</a></sup>).</p>\\n<p>Basically, I couldn\'t have come up with the ideas for this manifesto without having consumed, in my free time over the past 10 years:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>About 1,000 online courses and lectures by experts on just about every subject (and probably 5,000 less serious but sometimes interesting videos on YouTube)</li>\\n<li>At least 300 Wikipedia pages (and probably 500 additional readings on other sites and blogs)</li>\\n<li>Over 300 books summarizing the best of 5,000 years of history, scientific research, and human experience (not counting the roughly thousand others I simply skimmed or read a detailed summary of generated by AI)</li>\\n<li>And all the information I was able to gather by bombarding everyone I met (at least 200 people) with questions, particularly online</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>I would like to take this opportunity to thank the thousands of scientists, academics, and self-taught individuals for their work, without which this manifesto simply could not have come into being. Essentially, all I did was take all of their work and my own experiences, reflect on them, and bring it all together into a coherent, comprehensive vision.</p>\\n<p>That said, we can take it even further. Alongside this access to information, it would have been impossible for me to develop my ideas, organize them into a coherent outline, and finally write them down without a computer, a smartphone, the internet, and free note-taking software like <a href=\\"https://obsidian.md/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Obsidian</a>. It\'s a bit strange to say, but I think it would have been humanly impossible to conceive the theories I\'m going to present in this manifesto and to unify them into a coherent written vision without these digital tools.</p>\\n<p>Concretely, if I had had to take notes by hand on sheets of paper, it would surely have taken me a few more years to complete this manifesto. Because I would have wasted 5 minutes every time I wanted to find a note, instead of simply searching with CTRL+F or clicking on a web link in my browser\'s bookmarks. But, above all, since my human intellectual capacity is limited, my memory would eventually have become overwhelmed by the multitude of sheets of notes, and I would have been unable to find certain notes and thus to make connections between certain ideas. As a result, I would simply have been unable to conceive of the theories and the manifesto you are currently reading.</p>\\n<p>This brings us back to our initial hypothesis: intellectuals may have given up in the face of the world\'s complexity because the world was truly too complex for the human mind. But the internet, computer science, AI, and—above all—the creation of high-quality content over the past decade (e.g. YouTube lectures) are changing the game by allowing us to:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>To learn much more and much faster on all subjects</li>\\n<li>To overcome the limits of the human brain\'s memory and information processing by relying on computer tools to store and reprocess the information we read and hear</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>In other words, human beings now have the tools necessary to tackle the complexity of the modern world<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-2\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-2\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">2</a></sup>. And I\'m not asking you to take my word for it. I hope this manifesto will serve as proof. And I\'m counting on you to validate my theory by showing the world what the human mind is capable of with new technologies. Concretely, I expect some of you to solve all the <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Millennium_Prize_Problems\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Millennium Problems</a> and surpass Einstein by unifying quantum physics and general relativity (something I would never have time to do, even if I were capable of it).</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"0673d593-99da-4505-bced-fcfa63b532ab\\">Human-Machine Hybridization for the Past 300,000 Years</h2>\\n<p>Some of you may have noticed something: I have just described a hybridization of man and machine. Yes, in the previous section, I literally admitted that this manifesto is the result of a hybridization between my brain, my computer, and the internet. Worse still, that human intelligence alone is too limited to tackle the challenges of the modern world. In short, that our only hope is to hybridize with the machine.</p>\\n<p>Unsurprisingly, this is simply one facet of the \\"sense of History\\" that leads us toward <em>ever greater intelligence</em>. This hybridization of humans with the \\"machine\\" is not new. Humans had already hybridized their minds with clay tablets (or paper) by inventing writing 5,000 years ago<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-3\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-3\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">3</a></sup>. And long before that, with <em>symbolic systems</em> by \\"inventing\\" language<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-4\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-4\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">4</a></sup>. The only difference between language, clay, paper, computing, or a chip implanted in the brain lies in issues of information management<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-5\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-5\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">5</a></sup> (speed of information transmission and processing, durability of stored information, ability to retrieve it, etc.).</p>\\n<p>Concretely, when writing this book, I was limited by:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>My typing speed, reading speed, ability to understand videos, and, above all, my ability to organize my notes and retrieve them using just a few keywords from among more than 300,000 words of notes.</li>\\n<li>Without computers, I would have been limited by my reading and writing speed with pen and paper, my access to books, and, above all, by my ability to organize my notes and remember them well enough to find them again.</li>\\n<li>Without writing, I would have been limited by my direct access to teachers and my brain\'s ability to manipulate words, symbols, or sentences and retain them in memory so I could develop my thoughts and recite them orally in a coherent speech.</li>\\n<li>And, without language, I would have been limited by my intuition\'s ability to associate images, sounds, or any other sensation, to retain the result in memory, and to communicate it through gestures and grunts. Furthermore, to understand the gestures and grunts of others.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>These \\"technical\\" advancements—language, writing, and computing—have each enabled humans to \\"shift into high gear\\", to use the analogy of a car engine. In other words, to think \\"faster\\" or \\"further\\" by harnessing the raw power of the human brain more efficiently. How is this possible, given that the brain itself has not evolved and still processes information at the same speed? By successfully compressing and structuring information into \\"ideas\\", in particular.</p>\\n<p>This brings us to a fundamental point:</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"385c02e7-ecc8-469a-ab38-7fbd710e7857\\">The Power of Ideas</h2>\\n<p>Imagine you never learned to count with numbers in school. Could you even conceive of the existence of \\"1 billion\\" of something? No. And that wouldn\'t be because your brain lacks power, but because you\'re unable to harness that power. It\'s as if you had a car with a 190-horsepower engine, but you were stuck in first gear and couldn\'t go faster than 60 km/h.</p>\\n<p>Does that mean we only use 10% of our brain? Biologically, no. But conceptually, yes, in a way. In reality, certain ideas allow us to harness the raw power of the human brain much more efficiently. With the same raw power, numbers let us manipulate mind-boggling quantities with precision—something that would be impossible without them. In other words, certain ideas, like numbers, literally make us smarter.</p>\\n<p>How? Specifically, by compressing information into one or more symbols. For example, \\"1 billion\\" symbolically represents a quantity that is impossible to visualize mentally. No human being can precisely conceive of \\"1 billion\\" of anything, let alone keep such a quantity in memory. But they can conceive of the symbol \\"1,000,000,000\\" and even perform mathematical operations on it.</p>\\n<p>Thus, ideas allow humans to overcome their intellectual limitations by using artificial tools. Knowing that numbers were created by humans, just like the calculator and the computer. Hence the historical continuity of the human-machine hybridization described earlier.</p>\\n<p>Now, not all ideas make one smarter. Not all ideas are \\"powerful\\". Here, the term \\"power\\" refers to the precision or \\"level of detail\\"<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-6\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-6\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">6</a></sup> with which an idea can describe reality. Concretely, numbers are more powerful ideas than \\"few\\" and \\"many\\" because they are more precise. Reciprocally, intelligence here is the ability to access a high level of detail. For understanding the world in detail is necessary to create complex things. For example, to invent computers, one first had to access the level of detail of electrons inside atoms.</p>\\n<p>This concept of \\"level of detail\\" is central to the rest of the book. Let\'s take a moment to illustrate it with a concrete example.</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"538ac8a1-a7d7-41d5-8b72-a0d4aa1d8538\\">The Level of Detail of Reality</h2>\\n<img src=\\"/media/lapin_level_detail.png\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>\\"polys\\" = polygons = triangles (source: <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mIkIMgEVnX0\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Game Dev Academy</a>).</em></p>\\n<p>In modern video games, the 3D graphics displayed on screen (backgrounds, characters, objects, etc.) are actually composed solely of triangles<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-7\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-7\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">7</a></sup>. And the more triangles there are, the higher the level of detail that can be achieved.</p>\\n<p>Some figures:</p>\\n<table>\\n<colgroup>\\n<col style=\\"max-width: 50px%\\">\\n<col style=\\"max-width: 50px%\\">\\n</colgroup>\\n<thead>\\n<tr>\\n<th><strong>Element</strong></th>\\n<th><strong>Number of triangles</strong> (approximate)</th>\\n</tr>\\n</thead>\\n<tbody>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Main character</td>\\n<td>50\xa0000 – 150\xa0000</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Weapon</td>\\n<td>2\xa0000 – 15\xa0000</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Small decorative item</td>\\n<td>100 – 1 000</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Tree or car</td>\\n<td>10\xa0000 – 50\xa0000</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Visible scene</td>\\n<td>500\xa0000 – 15\xa0000\xa0000</td>\\n</tr>\\n</tbody>\\n</table>\\n<p>The human eye cannot tell the difference between thousands of triangles with blurred edges<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-8\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-8\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">8</a></sup> and the curve of a rabbit\'s ear on the screen. Yet these differences do exist; what is displayed on the screen is not a curve, but slightly smoothed triangles. And this principle applies to all fields. All the objects around you right now are much more complex than they appear. For example, the book you\'re holding in your hands is actually made up of sheets of paper, which are themselves made up of molecules, which are themselves made up of atoms, and so on. And the same goes for you.</p>\\n<p>On a different note, we could also discuss the level of detail of countries:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Country</li>\\n<li>Region</li>\\n<li>City</li>\\n<li>Household</li>\\n<li>Individual</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>What is the point of these reflections? Let\'s go back to what we said earlier: <em>some ideas literally make you smarter</em>. Could it be that understanding the concept of \\"level of detail\\" has made you smarter?</p>\\n<p>Yes. Of course, your brain hasn\'t become more powerful, but you can harness its power more effectively. In <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_and_crystallized_intelligence\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">more traditional terms</a>, your fluid intelligence hasn\'t changed (the brain\'s raw power), but your crystallized intelligence has (the knowledge that allows you to harness that power).</p>\\n<p>How? By now allowing you to use the concept of \\"level of detail\\" to think about or explain any other subject. And you can do this by using very simple visual examples to communicate your ideas. That is precisely what I have done. I used a 3D rabbit model to explain the concept of \\"level of detail\\", and I will often reuse this image throughout this book.</p>\\n<p>Now, where do the ideas that allow us to delve into ever greater levels of detail come from? In other words, where do the most powerful ideas—that is, the most precise ones—come from? From science, of course. Which brings us to the next point:</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"d15e9760-fd5d-49d3-a7d9-d7dcdcf5ae5e\\">The Scientific Sense of History</h2>\\n<p>Scientific progress can be defined as an increase in the level of detail of human knowledge. In other words, it is the gradual improvement of our understanding of the world. The difference between Newton\'s law of gravitation and Einstein\'s<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-9\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-9\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">9</a></sup>, lies in the level of detail:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>According to Newton, gravity is a force exerted by the mass of one celestial body on others: the heavier a celestial body is, the stronger the force it exerts on others</li>\\n<li>According to Einstein, this \\"force\\" is actually a distortion of spacetime caused by mass: the heavier a celestial body is, the more it distorts spacetime, which draws others toward it</li>\\n</ul>\\n<img src=\\"/media/cadran_newton_einstein_gravite.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 700px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>in the image at the bottom right, we can imagine that the small ball is drawn toward the large one, because the large one creates a large hole into which the small one will roll. The deeper this hole is, the faster the descent will be, and thus the stronger the gravitational pull will be.</em></p>\\n<p>In short, <a href=\\"https://youtube.com/playlist?list=PLK3v6vxQgv6SYzxABG4AcrYYAOgKTcIv3&#x26;si=Ze4mvKZUnSEBMcmE\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">what Einstein did</a>, was to successfully add the concept of spacetime to Newton\'s equation by using the latest mathematical advances of his time. As a result, while Newton\'s theory agreed with 99% of observations of the motion of planets and stars, Einstein\'s theory agrees with 99.99%<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-10\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-10\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">10</a></sup>. Thus, Einstein refined Newton\'s equation and increased the level of detail in human knowledge.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/lapin_newton_einstein_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n<p>There is a fundamental point here: contrary to popular belief, scientific revolutions do not generally destroy what came before. Einstein\'s theory did not invalidate Newton\'s theory; he refined it. In fact, Newton\'s theory is still taught in schools and will likely still be taught in 100 or 1,000 years, even as physics makes enormous progress. Quite simply, because Newton\'s theory describes reality almost as well as Einstein\'s in most cases, with the advantage of being much simpler.</p>\\n<p>More broadly speaking, most of the science courses taught in schools in France over the past 50 or even 100 years—such as chemistry—are still true today and will always remain so. For example, the Pythagorean theorem has been true for over 2,300 years and there is no reason why it won\'t still be true in 10,000 years. This means one thing: scientific truths exist. So let\'s ask ourselves a question: what are scientific truths based on?</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"af9e9d6d-3fb5-45e3-a274-414b63a8c341\\">The Natural Selection of Ideas</h2>\\n<p>First, let\'s review what natural selection is: natural selection is the mechanism by which individuals best adapted to their environment are more likely to survive and reproduce, thereby passing on their traits to the next generation. In other words, the life forms best adapted to their environment survive, while the others generally end up disappearing. For example, in a population of insects, those resistant to pesticides survive better than the others. As a result, the insect population gradually becomes resistant to pesticides, because those that are not resistant die without leaving offspring, while the others multiply.</p>\\n<p>Building on this, here is how we might define the natural selection of ideas: the most \\"credible and useful\\"<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-11\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-11\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">11</a></sup> ideas survive better than others and eventually prevail everywhere. For example:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>The ancient theory that every substance in the universe is composed of one or more of the four elements (earth, water, air, and fire) has disappeared</li>\\n<li>Whereas the atomic theory, with electrons, protons, and neutrons, has become established across the globe</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>The reason is simple: the first does not reflect reality and is of little practical use, whereas the second accurately describes reality and is the foundation of the modern world. Among other things, it has made possible:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Chemistry: medicines, plastics, agricultural fertilizers, etc.</li>\\n<li>Electronics and computing: semiconductors, transistors, computers, smartphones, the internet, etc.</li>\\n<li>Energy: the design of batteries, nuclear power plants, etc.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Now, how does the natural selection of ideas work? In other words, how does humanity select the most credible and useful ideas? First, usefulness is often demonstrated empirically, since it is difficult to predict the usefulness of an idea before using it—that is, before experimenting with it. Second, credibility rests on the three fundamental principles of science:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>The principle of consistency: consistency within the theory and between the theory and observations</li>\\n<li>The principle of falsifiability: the theory\'s claims or predictions must be testable (and thus validatable or falsifiable)</li>\\n<li>The principle of reproducibility: experiments validating or falsifying a theory must be reproducible (and thus verifiable independently of a centralized authority)</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Theories that do not adhere to these principles are not credible and are unlikely to survive, particularly within scientific and professional circles. For example, no one would invest 10 billion euros in building a nuclear power plant based on an incoherent and untested theory.</p>\\n<p>That said, we have just seen how humanity selects credible and useful ideas, but not how it creates them. This raises a question: where do ideas come from? In the natural selection of species, it is genetic mutations that generate new characteristics and allow species to evolve. In the case at hand: how do ideas and theories evolve?</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"904d04fc-2b44-4035-909b-5da6a889d2ab\\">On the Origin of Ideas</h2>\\n<img src=\\"/media/information_cerveau_id\xe9e_startup_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n<p>The idea I will present in this section and the next is this: <em>the human brain is an \\"information processing system\\", much like a computer. It generates ideas, solutions, or theories only based on the information we feed it and, in particular, on what it has learned.</em></p>\\n<p>To introduce this idea, let\'s ask ourselves a question: why have so many of the innovative startups of the past 20 years been founded or co-founded by students from the most prestigious schools?</p>\\n<br>\\n<table style=\\"max-width:67px%;\\">\\n<colgroup>\\n<col style=\\"max-width: 33px%\\">\\n<col style=\\"max-width: 33px%\\">\\n</colgroup>\\n<thead>\\n<tr>\\n<th><strong>Startup</strong></th>\\n<th><strong>University of at least one of the founders</strong></th>\\n</tr>\\n</thead>\\n<tbody>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Google</td>\\n<td>Stanford</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Paypal</td>\\n<td>Stanford</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Facebook</td>\\n<td>Harvard</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Instagram</td>\\n<td>Stanford</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Stripe</td>\\n<td>Harvard and MIT</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Airbnb</td>\\n<td>Harvard</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>OpenAI</td>\\n<td>Stanford</td>\\n</tr>\\n</tbody>\\n</table>\\n<p>Answer: Because they were the first to come up with the ideas (even before discussing the resources needed to implement them). But why did students at the most prestigious schools come up with the idea before others? Because they had access to information before others, given that \\"information\\" spreads first to the top schools—or even spreads only to those schools.</p>\\n<p>Concretely, scientists and business leaders at the forefront of their fields travel exclusively to the top schools to share their experience. The chances of seeing a world-renowned scientist give a lecture at a second-tier university are virtually nil. And, if it did happen, it would occur several months, or even several years, after their visit to the top schools. As a result, by the time the average student discovers an opportunity, Harvard students will have already founded their startup several years prior. This head start will ensure their success, because in a game where everyone is roughly equal and works just as hard, victory<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-12\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-12\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">12</a></sup> goes to those who benefit from an \\"unfair advantage\\"<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-13\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-13\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">13</a></sup>, in this case, access to information (note that the internet is reducing this advantage, even though it remains significant today).</p>\\n<p>The point I want to make here is that coming up with an innovative idea isn\'t so much a matter of genius, hard work, or money as it is of access to information. In a way, a revolutionary idea is just one more step up the stairs of knowledge built on previous discoveries. And that step is never very big.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/escalier_connaissance.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 400px;\\" />\\n<p><em>\\"If I have seen further, it is because I have stood on the shoulders of giants.\\"</em><br>\\nIsaac Newton</p>\\n<p>For example, Newton was originally interested in the ballistics<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-14\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-14\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">14</a></sup> of cannons. And, after learning everything there was to know on the subject, he simply asked himself: <em>\\"What would happen if <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lnEdBE7d_h0\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">I fired a cannonball really, really hard (knowing that the Earth is round)</a>?\\"</em> He then realized that this ball could fall forever and thus orbit the Earth indefinitely. In short, that \\"the Moon and a cannonball are the same thing\\". The theory of gravity was born. It was \\"one small step for man, one giant leap for mankind\\".</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/principia_newton.jpg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 400px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>excerpt from Principia Mathematica (1728), in which Newton illustrates what would happen if cannonballs were fired with increasing force from the summit of a very high mountain (point “V”). You can recreate this experiment in this <a href=\\"https://explorables.scienceetonnante.com/newton-cannon/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">little game</a> (image source: <a href=\\"https://library.si.edu/image-gallery/100299\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Smithsonian Libraries</a>).</em></p>\\n<p>Now, of course, taking that small step required a bit of genius, but first and foremost, it required knowledge of previous discoveries. In other words, it required access to information. To support this idea, let\'s look at three other examples.</p>\\n<p>Why did Vitalik Buterin become passionate about cryptocurrencies at age 17 and co-create the cryptocurrency Ethereum at age 19 in 2014? Because his father, a computer scientist working in finance, told him about it and advised him to take an interest in it when he was 17. As a result, Vitalik Buterin became interested in cryptocurrencies before anyone else and became a millionaire in 2015, then a billionaire in 2021. Meanwhile, the majority of the population didn\'t hear about Bitcoin seriously for the first time until 2017 and didn\'t start investing until 2020, only to lose everything<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-15\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-15\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">15</a></sup>.</p>\\n<br>\\n<img src=\\"/media/von_neumann.jpg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 600px;\\" />\\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> <em>Robert Oppenheimer (left) and John von Neumann (right) (source: <a href=\\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Oppenheimer_and_von_Neumann_in_front_of_the_IAS_machine.jpg\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Jeremy Norman</a>)</em></p>\\n<p>Next, let\'s talk about John von Neumann, a mathematician and physicist who helped create the first atomic bomb, laid the foundations of quantum mechanics, and established the basis for modern computers (see: <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Von_Neumann_architecture\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">von Neumann architecture</a>). Some claim that even Einstein considered him an extraordinary genius. Now that we\'ve introduced him, let\'s look at a key aspect of his youth: his parents invited Hungary\'s intellectual elite to dinner every night, allowing young John to engage in free-flowing conversation with them from a very young age. To this, we must of course add that his very wealthy parents spent a fortune to provide him with the best possible education. Unsurprisingly, John von Neumann found himself ahead of his peers and graduated at the top of his class in college. He then went on to actively contribute to scientific research under the mentorship of the greatest scientists of his time.</p>\\n<p>Finally, let\'s take the example of the famous Indian mathematician Ramanujan (who even had a movie made about him: <em>The Man Who Knew Infinity</em>). Legend has it that he was born into a poor family and taught himself mathematics. The reality is that he was born into a Brahmin family, that is, one of the two highest castes in India (the equivalent of the clergy in Europe<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-16\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-16\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">16</a></sup>). And that his parents hosted students from one of the most prestigious universities in their region for several years. It was these students who would lend him his first math books, after passing on everything they knew to him orally. In other words, Ramanujan had highly qualified private tutors in his early years. This enabled him to quickly gain enough confidence in mathematics to continue learning on his own and eventually come up with new ideas.</p>\\n<p>These three examples show that before you can come up with new, meaningful ideas, you have to absorb a vast amount of knowledge. And that \\"geniuses\\" have generally had the opportunity to learn a great deal very quickly. Once again, the brain is nothing more than an information processing system. For Vitalik\'s brain to invent Ethereum, Vitalik had to absorb a massive amount of math and computer science, in addition to understanding how Bitcoin and its ecosystem work. And it\'s exactly the same for all scientific discoveries, startup ideas, and solutions in general. Before the minds of John von Neumann, Ramanujan, or startup founders came up with new ideas, they had to learn a great deal. Similarly, for Einstein to develop his theory of gravity, he first had to study Newton\'s theory and a multitude of experiments from his time, particularly the one that had already demonstrated the constancy of the speed of light.</p>\\n<p>More broadly, the human brain produces new ideas only from what is fed into it. And the computer science adage \\"garbage in, garbage out\\" applies perfectly to the human brain. If you feed erroneous or absurd data into a computer program, you will get an erroneous or absurd result. Which brings us to the next point:</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"10ea7338-15d8-46de-bdd2-d17470b72b44\\">How to Be a Visionary Like Steve Jobs</h2>\\n<p>When it comes to the human brain, the \\"garbage in, garbage out\\" principle holds true: the information that enters our brain determines what we think and even our view of the world. Concretely, if you spend your days listening to conspiracy theories, you\'ll become a conspiracy theorist. And if you listen only to doomsday environmentalist speech, you\'ll be convinced that the world is ending.</p>\\n<p>To illustrate just how much the information we consume shapes our worldview, let\'s take the example of the \\"visionary\\" Steve Jobs. Here\'s a quote from the Wikipedia page on Steve Jobs:</p>\\n<p><em>\\"Larry Lang, an engineer who lived a hundred yards from their old house and at whose home Jobs spent many evenings, invited him to join the Hewlett-Packard Explorers Club<sup><a href=\\"#user-content-fn-17\\" id=\\"user-content-fnref-17\\" data-footnote-ref=\\"\\" aria-describedby=\\"footnote-label\\">17</a></sup>. Fifteen students would gather there every Tuesday evening in the company cafeteria and invite a computer engineer from the company to talk about his work. Following one of these talks, he invited one of the students to visit his lab; it was on this occasion that the young Steve saw the first desktop computer Hewlett-Packard was developing, the 9100A. At the age of thirteen, he didn\'t hesitate to call William Hewlett, the president of the company that bears part of his name. Steve was building a frequency meter and needed parts. They talked for twenty minutes; Hewlett sent him the components he needed and offered him a summer job at his company. After his freshman year at Homestead High, Steve Jobs thus spent the summer working on one of Hewlett-Packard\'s assembly lines.\\"</em></p>\\n<p>In other words, Steve Jobs\' worldview was shaped by what he knew was possible. He didn\'t predict the democratization of personal computers before others for mystical reasons or simply because of his \\"genius\\". Rather, it was because he discovered what was possible before others did, through direct contact with the pioneers of computing. On top of that, he lived right where History was being made: Silicon Valley.</p>\\n<p>Let\'s wrap up these last two sections. The goal was to show that the human mind is an \\"information processing system\\". In other words, it generates new ideas and solutions solely from the information it receives. There is no magic involved. All human progress is based on this information processing.</p>\\n<p>However, information is worthless without consciousness and willpower. Whether it\'s Steve Jobs, Vitalik Buterin, John von Neumann, Ramanujan, or startup founders, they all worked incredibly hard. Because, while our brain is an \\"information processing system\\", we still have to process that information and do something with it. The case of Steve Jobs fits quite well with a passage from Nassim Nicholas Taleb\'s book <em>Antifragile</em>:</p>\\n<p><em>\\"A prophet is not the first to have an idea, but the first to believe in it—and to strive to bring it to fruition.\\"</em></p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/information_conscience_id\xe9e_startup_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 800px;\\" />\\n<p>In other words, while it is true that the human brain is an \\"information processing system\\", that does not cover the whole picture. We are more than just a machine that processes information. We have consciousness. And it is on the information-processing work carried out by this consciousness that all human progress rests. That is, on what we consciously do with information. Which brings us to the final question of this chapter: what is consciousness?</p>\\n<h2 id=\\"11a1a615-91ca-45ea-b19d-55ddd8a44176\\">The Evolution of Consciousness</h2>\\n<p>In this final section, I will present two ideas:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Consciousness is an \\"inner workspace\\"</li>\\n<li>The sense of the universe continually enriches the content of consciousness</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Let\'s begin with a summary of the history of life (we will explore this history in detail in Chapter 5). Over the course of evolution, living organisms have become increasingly capable of adapting to and responding to their environment. First, simply by adapting genetically through natural selection, and then by becoming capable of gathering information about their immediate environment to adjust their behavior. Concretely, flies and mosquitoes perceive movement and are thus able to fly away quickly when you try to swat them. Meanwhile, inert matter like a rock perceives nothing and does not react.</p>\\n<img src=\\"/media/fleche_pierre__degre_liberte_en.svg\\" style=\\"display:block;width:100%;height:auto;max-height:70dvh;object-fit:contain;margin-block:1rem;margin:auto;max-width: 600px;\\" />\\n<p>This ability to perceive information and process it in order to adapt to one\'s environment has become increasingly complex and sophisticated, reaching its peak in humans after 3.8 billion years of evolution. While the fly merely reacts, humans possess a true \\"inner workspace\\" that allows them to reflect long after they have received information. And even to construct in their minds before constructing in reality.</p>\\n<p>It is this \\"inner workspace\\" that we call consciousness. In this regard, let us quote two passages from the book <em>Consciousness and the Brain</em> by Stanislas Dehaene (a neuroscientist specializing in consciousness):</p>\\n<p><em>\\"Psychologist Bernard Baars calls it the \\"global workspace\\": an internal system, decoupled from the external world, within which we are free to create our own mental images and transmit them to any specialized brain processor.\\" [...] Everything we become aware of, we can keep in mind long after it has disappeared from our sensory organs. Once the information has been conveyed to the workspace, it remains there, regardless of when and where we initially perceived it. We can then use it in a thousand ways, and in particular send it to the language centers, thus naming it: this is why the ability to put into words what we have perceived is an excellent criterion of consciousness. We can also store it in our long-term memory or integrate it into our plans of action, whatever they may be. The flexible dissemination of information characterizes the conscious state.\\"</em></p>\\n<p>The evolution of this \\"inner workspace\\" from the origin of life to the richness of human consciousness is a facet of the sense of History that advances consciousness. That is to say, it continually enriches the content of consciousness. Here is an excerpt <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U4lB2vahe9A\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">from a lecture</a> by Stanislas Dehaene at the Coll\xe8ge de France:</p>\\n<p><em>\\"I think there is something new about the human species, but what is new is not the mechanism of consciousness. [...] What is new is the content of consciousness. As a human species, we have access to richer content than other animals. [...] We have symbols and a grammar to combine these symbols with one another, and this allows us to create thought content that is much richer than that of other animals.\\"</em></p>\\n<p>This notion of \\"content of consciousness\\" may seem a bit abstract at first glance. Yet it refers to the most concrete thing of all: human experience. And that is what we will explore in the next chapter by addressing the following questions: how do human beings perceive the world, think, create, find solutions and advance humanity concretely?</p>","toc":[{"id":"b9c5ecc1-6be0-4582-a85d-2ff30a0eaf87","text":"","level":1,"children":[{"id":"f02b72a5-ee6a-45b2-a44f-25d6417e1c72","text":"Introduction","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"2dba957d-d122-4740-8303-6ccaf607089b","text":"Why is the Current Intellectual Collapse an Optical Illusion?","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"ad4b9403-c99c-4dbb-90cd-2a7098edcaec","text":"At the Dawn of an Intellectual Revolution","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"0673d593-99da-4505-bced-fcfa63b532ab","text":"Human-Machine Hybridization for the Past 300,000 Years","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"385c02e7-ecc8-469a-ab38-7fbd710e7857","text":"The Power of Ideas","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"538ac8a1-a7d7-41d5-8b72-a0d4aa1d8538","text":"The Level of Detail of Reality","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"d15e9760-fd5d-49d3-a7d9-d7dcdcf5ae5e","text":"The Scientific Sense of History","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"af9e9d6d-3fb5-45e3-a274-414b63a8c341","text":"The Natural Selection of Ideas","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"904d04fc-2b44-4035-909b-5da6a889d2ab","text":"On the Origin of Ideas","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"10ea7338-15d8-46de-bdd2-d17470b72b44","text":"How to Be a Visionary Like Steve Jobs","level":2,"children":[]},{"id":"11a1a615-91ca-45ea-b19d-55ddd8a44176","text":"The Evolution of Consciousness","level":2,"children":[]}]}],"footnotes":"<hr>\\n<section data-footnotes=\\"\\" class=\\"footnotes\\"><h2 class=\\"sr-only\\" id=\\"\\">Footnotes</h2>\\n<ol>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-1\\">\\n<p>A direct parallel can be drawn with monastic life in the Middle Ages, when a \\"brother\\" would read the Bible to the others during meals (see, for example, the <a href=\\"https://www.osmthfrance.fr/etre-templier-aujourd-hui/138-la-regle-latine.html\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Rule of the Order of the Knights Templar </a>: <em>\\"Article 9: On Reading During Meals.\\"</em>). <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-1\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 1\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-2\\">\\n<p>Current AI models are expected to lead to a scientific revolution, much like the microscope and the telescope did in their time. For example, we can easily predict an explosion in historical research, given that AI will increase historians\' productivity by a factor of 2, 10, and perhaps even 100. In fact, if anyone from the \xc9cole des Chartes (or elsewhere) sends me a link to content showcasing AI applications for historical research, I will be happy to share it here. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-2\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 2\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-3\\">\\n<p>Writing is a tool that allows us to construct richer and more complex thoughts by transcending the limits of human memory. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-3\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 3\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-4\\">\\n<p>One of the fundamental differences between <em>Homo sapiens</em> (and Neanderthals <em>a priori</em>) and the rest of the <em>Homo</em> lineage is precisely the possession of vocal cords that enable complex articulate language. We can therefore consider <em>Homo sapiens</em> to be a species resulting from natural selection for the ability to use language within the <em>Homo</em> genus. In other words, <em>Homo sapiens</em> is literally the result of a hybridization between humans and language. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-4\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 4\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-5\\">\\n<p>As far as I know, I don\'t see how a chip implanted in the brain could improve our intellectual performance. The human brain\'s \\"reading\\" capabilities already reach their limit when faced with a video played at speed x2. And the limiting factor in \\"writing\\" is most often due to the mental design work, not the speed of writing by hand or on a keyboard. To overcome these limitations, we would need to create an interface capable of interacting directly with our biological neural networks, but for now, that\'s science fiction. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-5\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 5\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-6\\">\\n<p>We could also use the term \\"granularity\\", but \\"level of detail\\" seems clearer to me. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-6\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 6\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-7\\">\\n<p>This <a href=\\"https://youtube.com/playlist?list=PL9V1oyvT8aPwXSj-J3b2OQgcwP63u3f4R&#x26;si=hX78dr7mEqpDD5TQ\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">series of 3 videos</a> from the YouTube channel <em>Quantale</em> provides an interesting introduction to graphics modeling in video games: <em>\\"Create a 3D graphics engine.\\"</em> <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-7\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 7\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-8\\">\\n<p>There are many techniques for improving the final graphic rendering of these triangles, such as <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spatial_anti-aliasing\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">anti-aliasing</a>. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-8\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 8\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-9\\">\\n<p>Here are two introductory videos, one for each theory: <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mZWA2UetWAg\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Newton\'s</a> and <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E5LvA8FHBxs\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Einstein\'s</a>. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-9\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 9\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-10\\">\\n<p>I chose 99% and 99.99% to make it easier to understand. In reality, Einstein\'s theory is up to 10\xb9\xb9 (1 followed by 11 zeros) times more accurate than Newton\'s for certain observations. This simply means that Newton\'s theory is unable to explain certain observations. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-10\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 10\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-11\\">\\n<p>To explore this idea further, I recommend two videos <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ACWEAdi7wAo&#x26;list=PLtzmb84AoqRTl0m1b82gVLcGU38miqdrC&#x26;index=6\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\"><em>Logic Is Not Enough</em></a> by L\xea Nguy\xean Hoang (mathematician and videographer for the YouTube channel <em>Science4All</em>). In summary: <em>\\"Fundamental physical laws are largely incapable of predicting phenomena on a macroscopic scale, as they require completely unrealistic computation times. What we need are \\"emergent\\" theories whose scope of validity will necessarily be limited and whose predictions will not be entirely reliable, but at least these predictions will be computable within a reasonable time frame. And, in particular, […] it does not seem relevant to judge the \\"truth\\" of theories. What seems more relevant is to judge their credibility and usefulness.\\"</em> And the video <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=itRV2jEtV8Q\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\"><em>Simulating a Phase Transition</em></a> by Vilas Winstein and 3Blue1Brown: <em>\\"This simulation, with just 200 particles, took several hours to compute. Even the most powerful computers couldn\'t solve this problem if the number of particles were on the order of 10 billion, or 10^10. It\'s just too many calculations. And by the way, 10 billion isn\'t even close to the typical number of particles in anything we interact with. In just one teaspoon of water, the number of water molecules is around 10^23.\\"</em> <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-11\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 11\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-12\\">\\n<p>In the world of entrepreneurship, the \\"winners take all\\". Consequently, startups founded by students from second-tier schools will not succeed to some extent or moderately, but not at all. This principle applies just as ruthlessly in science. History remembers only the name of the first person to have had a revolutionary idea and to have spread it. The best-known example is that of Alfred Russel Wallace, who developed the theory of evolution by natural selection at the same time as Charles Darwin. Yet we know only Charles Darwin, because he was the first to write a book to make his theory known to the general public: <em>On the Origin of Species</em>. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-12\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 12\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-13\\">\\n<p>To take this further, we could also mention the concept of \\"<a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_moat\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">moat</a>\\", which refers to a sustainable competitive advantage. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-13\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 13\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-14\\">\\n<p>Ballistics is the science that studies the motion of projectiles (cannonballs, rifle bullets, missiles, etc.). <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-14\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 14\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-15\\">\\n<p>Cryptocurrencies, like any speculative system, are a system for redistributing wealth from the majority to a minority. Fundamentally, in a stock market crash, money does not disappear. Everyone who lost simply transferred their money to a minority of winners. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-15\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 15\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-16\\">\\n<p>The Brahmins correspond to the function of priests, and thus of the clergy in the <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trifunctional_hypothesis\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">Indo-European tripartite division</a>: nobility, clergy, and the third estate. In most cases, members of the clergy were wealthier than the majority of the population, which consisted of farmworkers. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-16\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 16\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li id=\\"user-content-fn-17\\">\\n<p>Hewlett-Packard, founded in 1939, became the world\'s leading computer manufacturer in 2006 and remained so until 2013, when it was dethroned by Lenovo. <a href=\\"#user-content-fnref-17\\" data-footnote-backref=\\"\\" aria-label=\\"Back to reference 17\\" class=\\"data-footnote-backref\\"><svg class=\\"footnote-backref-icon\\" xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\" viewBox=\\"0 0 24 24\\" fill=\\"none\\" stroke=\\"currentColor\\" stroke-width=\\"2\\" stroke-linecap=\\"round\\" stroke-linejoin=\\"round\\"><path d=\\"M9 10 4 15l5 5\\"/><path d=\\"M20 4v7a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H4\\"/></svg></a></p>\\n</li>\\n</ol>\\n</section>","frontmatter":{}}}')}}]);